<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="ch4-section-rotating-reference-frame" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Rotating reference frame</title>

    <p>
        Consider a vector <m>\vec{A}</m> in three-dimensional space.
        Any coordinate system (e.g., Cartesian, local Cartesian, cylindrical, standard spherical)
        could serve as a reference frame to investigate <m>\vec{A}</m>.
        While the unit direction vectors of coordinate systems differ,
        and consequently the components of a given vector differ among coordinate systems,
        all coordinate systems can be used to describe the same vector.
    </p>

    <p>
        Consider two Cartesian coordinate systems:
        One is non-accelerating,
        and the other is rotating relative to the first with constant angular velocity <m>\vec{\Omega}</m>.
        The former is an inertial reference frame and will be indicated by the subscript "abs".
        The latter is a non-inertial reference frame and will be indicated by the subscript "rot".
    </p>

    <p>
        The inertial coordinate system is assigned unit direction vectors <m>\hat{i}_{abs}</m>,
        <m>\hat{j}_{abs}</m>,
        and <m>\hat{k}_{abs}</m>,
        and the rotating coordinate system is assigned unit direction vectors <m>\hat{i}_{rot}</m>,
        <m>\hat{j}_{rot}</m>,
        and <m>\hat{k}_{rot}</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
        In the inertial coordinate system
    </p>

    <p>
        <md xml:id="eqn-inertial-vector" number="yes">
            \vec{A}
            =
            A_{x,abs} \, \hat{i}_{abs}
            + A_{y,abs} \, \hat{j}_{abs}
            + A_{z,abs} \, \hat{k}_{abs}
        </md>
    </p>

    <p>
        and in the rotating coordinate system
    </p>

    <p>
        <md xml:id="eqn-noninertial-vector" number="yes">
            \vec{A}
            =
            A_{x,rot} \, \hat{i}_{rot}
            + A_{y,rot} \, \hat{j}_{rot}
            + A_{z,rot} \, \hat{k}_{rot}
        </md>
    </p>

    <p>
        Both <xref ref="eqn-inertial-vector" text="type-global" />
        and <xref ref="eqn-noninertial-vector" text="type-global" />
        are equally valid expressions for <m>\vec{A}</m>:
        Even though the values of their components differ,
        they each describe the same vector.
    </p>

    <p>
        Let <m>\vec{A}</m> change with time,
        i.e., let <m>\vec{A} = \vec{A}(t)</m>.
        In the inertial coordinate system,
        which itself is not accelerating and therefore has unchanging unit direction vectors,
    </p>

    <p>
        <md xml:id="eqn-inertial-derivative-general" number="yes">
            \frac{D \vec{A}}{Dt}
            =
            \frac{D A_{x,abs}}{Dt} \, \hat{i}_{abs}
            + \frac{D A_{y,abs}}{Dt} \, \hat{j}_{abs}
            + \frac{D A_{z,abs}}{Dt} \, \hat{k}_{abs}
        </md>
    </p>

    <p>
        We call the expression on the right-hand side of <xref ref="eqn-inertial-derivative-general" text="type-global" />
        <m>\left( \dfrac{D\vec{A}}{Dt} \right)_{abs}</m>
        since it describes how <m>\vec{A}</m> is changing with time relative to the inertial coordinate system:
    </p>

    <p>
        <md xml:id="eqn-inertial-derivative-specific" number="yes">
            \left( \frac{D \vec{A}}{Dt} \right)_{abs}
            =
            \frac{D A_{x,abs}}{Dt} \, \hat{i}_{abs}
            + \frac{D A_{y,abs}}{Dt} \, \hat{j}_{abs}
            + \frac{D A_{z,abs}}{Dt} \, \hat{k}_{abs}
        </md>
    </p>

    <p>
        <xref ref="eqn-inertial-derivative-general" text="type-global" />
        and <xref ref="eqn-inertial-derivative-specific" text="type-global" />
        make it clear that
    </p>

    <p>
        <md xml:id="eqn-inertial-derivative-equality" number="yes">
            \frac{D \vec{A}}{Dt} = \left( \dfrac{D\vec{A}}{Dt} \right)_{abs}
        </md>
    </p>

    <p>
        Since the rotating coordinate system itself accelerates,
        its unit direction vectors change orientation with time relative to the inertial coordinate system,
        and so by product rule,
    </p>

    <p>
        <md>
            <mrow>
                \frac{D \vec{A}}{Dt} \amp
                = \frac{D A_{x,rot}}{Dt} \, \hat{i}_{rot} + A_{x,rot} \, \frac{D \hat{i}_{rot}}{Dt}
            </mrow>
            <mrow>\amp \quad + \frac{D A_{y,rot}}{Dt} \, \hat{j}_{rot} + A_{y,rot} \, \frac{D \hat{j}_{rot}}{Dt}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp \quad + \frac{D A_{z,rot}}{Dt} \, \hat{k}_{rot} + A_{z,rot} \, \frac{D \hat{k}_{rot}}{Dt}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp = 
                \left( 
                    \frac{D A_{x,rot}}{Dt} \, \hat{i}_{rot}
                    + \frac{D A_{y,rot}}{Dt} \, \hat{j}_{rot}
                    + \frac{D A_{z,rot}}{Dt} \, \hat{k}_{rot}
                \right)
            </mrow>
            <mrow xml:id="eqn-noninertial-derivative-general" number="yes">
                \amp \quad +
                \left( 
                    A_{x,rot} \, \frac{D \hat{i}_{rot}}{Dt}
                    + A_{y,rot} \, \frac{D \hat{j}_{rot}}{Dt}
                    + A_{z,rot} \, \frac{D \hat{k}_{rot}}{Dt}
                \right)
            </mrow>
        </md>
    </p>

    <p>
        We call the first expression in parentheses on the right-hand side of <xref ref="eqn-noninertial-derivative-general" text="type-global" />
        <m>\left( \dfrac{D\vec{A}}{Dt} \right)_{rot}</m>
        since it describes how <m>\vec{A}</m> is changing relative to the rotating coordinate system:
    </p>

    <p>
        <md xml:id="eqn-noninertial-derivative-specific-intermediate" number="yes">
            \left( \frac{D \vec{A}}{Dt} \right)_{rot}
            =
            \frac{D A_{x,rot}}{Dt} \, \hat{i}_{rot}
            + \frac{D A_{y,rot}}{Dt} \, \hat{j}_{rot}
            + \frac{D A_{z,rot}}{Dt} \, \hat{k}_{rot}
        </md>
    </p>

    <p>
        But because of the second expression in parentheses on the right-hand side of
        <xref ref="eqn-noninertial-derivative-general" text="type-global" />,
        <xref ref="eqn-noninertial-derivative-general" text="type-global" />
        and <xref ref="eqn-noninertial-derivative-specific-intermediate" text="type-global" />
        make it clear that
    </p>

    <p>
        <md xml:id="eqn-noninertial-derivative-inequality" number="yes">
            \frac{D \vec{A}}{Dt} \neq \left( \dfrac{D\vec{A}}{Dt} \right)_{rot}
        </md>
    </p>

    <p>
        The second expression on in parentheses on the right-hand side of
        <xref ref="eqn-noninertial-derivative-general" text="type-global" />
        arises because the unit direction vectors rotate with their coordinate system at <m>\vec{\Omega}</m>.
        It follows from the definition of tangential velocity <m>\vec{v}_T</m> for uniform circular motion
    </p>

    <p>
        <md>
            \vec{v_T} = \vec{\Omega} \times \vec{r}
        </md>
    </p>

    <p>
        that
    </p>
    
    <p>
        <md>
             \frac{D \hat{i}_{rot}}{Dt} = \vec{\Omega} \times \hat{i}_{rot}
        </md>
    </p>

    <p>
        <md>
            \frac{D \hat{j}_{rot}}{Dt} = \vec{\Omega} \times \hat{j}_{rot}
        </md>
    </p>

    <p>
        <md>
            \frac{D \hat{k}_{rot}}{Dt} = \vec{\Omega} \times \hat{k}_{rot}
        </md>
    </p>

    <p>
        (The full derivation of these terms is shown in <xref ref="appendix-cross-product-term-proof" text="type-global" />.)
        Therefore,
        the second expression in parenthesis on the right-hand side of
        <xref ref="eqn-noninertial-derivative-general" text="type-global" />
        becomes
    </p>

    <p>
        <md>
            <mrow>
                A_{x,rot} \, \frac{D \hat{i}_{rot}}{Dt}
                + A_{y,rot} \, \frac{D \hat{j}_{rot}}{Dt}
                + A_{z,rot} \, \frac{D \hat{k}_{rot}}{Dt}
                \amp =
                A_{x,rot} \left( \vec{\Omega} \times \hat{i}_{rot} \right)
                + A_{y,rot} \left( \vec{\Omega} \times \hat{j}_{rot} \right)
                + A_{z,rot} \left( \vec{\Omega} \times \hat{k}_{rot} \right)
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
                \amp =
                \vec{\Omega} \times
                \left( A_{x,rot} \, \hat{i}_{rot} \right)
                + \vec{\Omega} \times \left( A_{y,rot} \, \hat{j}_{rot} \right)
                + \vec{\Omega} \times \left( A_{z,rot} \, \hat{k}_{rot} \right)
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
                \amp =
                \vec{\Omega} \times
                 \left( A_{x,rot} \, \hat{i}_{rot}
                + A_{y,rot} \, \hat{j}_{rot}
                + A_{z,rot} \, \hat{k}_{rot} \right)
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
                \amp = 
                \vec{\Omega} \times \vec{A}
            </mrow>
        </md>
    </p>

    <p>
        where the scalar multiplication property of the cross product
    </p>

    <p>
        <md>
            k \left( \vec{a} \times \vec{b} \right) = \vec{a} \times \left( k \, \vec{b} \right)
        </md>
    </p>

    <p>
        as well as its distributive property over addition have been used
        (review these properties in <xref ref="ch1-section-calculus-subsection-vector-calculus-subsubsection-dot-cross-products" text="type-global" />).
    </p>

    <p>
        Thus, <xref ref="eqn-noninertial-derivative-general" text="type-global" /> becomes
    </p>

    <p>
        <md xml:id="eqn-noninertial-derivative-specific" number="yes">
            \frac{D\vec{A}}{Dt}
            =
            \left( \frac{D\vec{A}}{Dt} \right)_{rot}
            +
            \vec{\Omega} \times \vec{A}
        </md>
    </p>

    <p>
        and equating <xref ref="eqn-inertial-derivative-equality" text="type-global" />
        and <xref ref="eqn-noninertial-derivative-specific" text="type-global" />
        reveals
    </p>

    <p>
        <md xml:id="eqn-derivative-equality" number="yes">
            \left( \frac{D\vec{A}}{Dt} \right)_{abs}
            =
            \left( \frac{D\vec{A}}{Dt} \right)_{rot}
            +
            \vec{\Omega} \times \vec{A}
        </md>
    </p>

    <p>
        <xref ref="eqn-derivative-equality" text="type-global" />
        says the time rate of change of an arbitrary vector <m>\vec{A}</m> relative to an inertial reference frame
        is due to the time rate of change of the vector relative to a rotating reference frame
        as well as to the rotation of that reference frame;
        in particular, it results from their sum.
    </p>

</section>